          "body": "Verses 8-9 ground the chapter's promises in the most solemn act available in ancient legal discourse: a divine oath. God swears 'by His right hand and by His strong arm' — the same arm celebrated in Isaiah 51:9 and 52:10 as the arm that executed the exodus. The content of the oath is specific and earthy: never again will enemies eat Zion's grain or drink her wine. This is the direct reversal of the covenant curse of Deuteronomy 28:33 ('a people whom you do not know will eat the produce of your ground'). The restoration is not purely spiritual; it includes the physical fruit of the land restored to its rightful owners and offered in the courts of the sanctuary (62:9). The harvest and the sanctuary are reunited — labor and worship, creation and covenant, the material and the holy, converge in the eschatological scene. Douglas Stuart's observation (Word Biblical Commentary on Hosea-Jonah) that the prophets consistently refuse to spiritualize away the materiality of the covenant blessings applies here: God's oath covers grain and wine and the courts where they are enjoyed. The New Testament picks this up in the marriage-supper of the Lamb (Revelation 19:9) and in Jesus's own promise that He will drink the fruit of the vine 'new' in the kingdom of His Father (Matthew 26:29)."
